recordings.loc: Skidaway Island, Chatham County, GA USA
recordings.rmk: This chip note is regularly heard throughout the wintering season and is the only vocalization until just prior to spring migration when they begin singing.  My observation is that with this and other species overwintering are more vocal earlier in their arrival, and that in the case of (Myrtle) Yellow-rumps they appear to be more social at that time, concentrations thinning out throughout the winter months. The recording was made with a Sound Devices 722 and a Sennheiser ME64 placed under a tree.  I 'spished' a few times to get their attention and they dutifully came in.  The recording has been amplified since the note is weak, and noise reduction was employed.

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Natural sound. Bird perched on the terminal branch of the crown of a small tree near the house.
 
#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 1kHz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.
